<TITLE> Afghans flee ahead of offensive </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Afghanistan, Feb 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)-- Villagers in Helmand flee their homes ahead of a huge NATO offensive targeting the Taliban. PLEASE NOTE: THIS EDIT CONTAINS CONVERTED 4:3 MATERIAL Afghan villagers are on the move to find a safe place. These people are from Helmand province, an area foreign military commanders are calling the last Taliban enclave. More than 90 families have fled the region ahead of a massive US-Nato operation targeting the Taliban. As security forces carried out checks on vehicles villagers said their families welfare is their priority. (SOUNDBITE) (Pashto) ZALMY KHAN, DISPLACED AFGHAN FROM MARJA DISTRICT SAYING: "We left our village because of the upcoming fighting and bombardment. I want to save the lives of my children and the rest of my family." (SOUNDBITE) (PASHTO) HAJI AKHTAR MOHAMMAD, A RESIDENT OF MARJA SAYING: "The military operation was launched in our village in order to keep us from any possible danger. I decided to leave the village and we are heading to Lashkar Gah to rent a house." NATO forces including U.S marines are planning one of the biggest assaults in the eight year operation. It will be the first major show of force since Washington ordered 30,000 extra troops to the region. Forces plan to seize the area known for its illegal opium crop which helps fund the insurgency. As these villagers leave their homes and fields, they're leaving behind an area scarred by years of bloods
